<div class="body">
    <p class="lead">The scene plays out the same way everywhere. A number goes up on the screen — board meeting, leadership review, the Monday all-hands — and someone senior squints at it. "That can't be right." A pause. Someone checks. It isn't right: a stale extract, a doubled region, a filter that quietly fell off. The correction takes a day. The damage takes much longer, because from that meeting forward, every number from that team arrives with an asterisk nobody can see but everyone applies.</p>

    <p>Here's the uncomfortable arithmetic of that moment: the error itself was probably small, and probably rare. The team may have shipped five hundred correct numbers for every wrong one. It doesn't matter. Trust in reporting doesn't average — it erodes asymmetrically. A hundred correct reports earn a quiet, invisible credit; one public error spends it all at once, with interest. This is why "our data is 99% accurate" persuades no one. The 1% wasn't evenly distributed. It landed in front of the CFO.</p>

    <p class="pull">Trust doesn't average. A hundred quiet, correct reports earn a slow credit — one error found by leadership spends it all at once.</p>

    <h2>The discovery-point ladder.</h2>
    <span class="h2-sub">The same error, five different prices</span>

    <p>Take one error — say, a refresh that silently failed, leaving last week's numbers wearing this week's date — and run it through the five places it could be caught. <strong>At the builder's desk</strong>, it costs minutes: notice, re-run, done. Nobody else ever knows. <strong>By an automated check</strong> — a freshness flag, a total that doesn't reconcile — it costs minutes plus the time it took to write the check, once. <strong>In review before distribution</strong>, it costs an hour and a small internal "good catch." Still invisible to the business.</p>

    <p>Then the report ships, and the prices change category. <strong>Found by a reader</strong>, it costs a correction email, an apology, and a small withdrawal from the trust account — recoverable, if it's rare and handled well. <strong>Found by an executive, in a meeting, in front of others</strong> — that's the boardroom price. Now the cost isn't measured in hours. It's measured in every future meeting where someone says "let's double-check that before we act on it," in the shadow spreadsheets that start appearing because people want their own version of the number, in the slow reclassification of the data team from <em>source of answers</em> to <em>thing to verify</em>. We've written about <a href="/insights/dashboards-not-trusted/">why dashboards lose trust even when the data is correct</a>; an error caught downstream is how the data stops being treated as correct even when it is.</p>

