    <h2>Why "perfect data" is the wrong goal.</h2>
    <span class="h2-sub">Quality is risk management, not purity</span>

    <p>The instinctive response to a public error is to declare war on errors — a data quality initiative, a tool evaluation, a goal of zero defects. It's the wrong frame. Perfect data doesn't exist in any organization that's actually moving: systems sync on different schedules, humans key things in, upstream vendors change formats without warning, and <a href="/insights/manual-reporting-trap/">every manual assembly step is its own standing error surface</a>. Chasing purity is an endless project with no finish line, and it usually collapses into either exhaustion or theater.</p>

    <p>The achievable goal is different and much more specific: <strong>errors that matter get caught before distribution, and the ones that slip through get handled in a way that builds trust instead of spending it.</strong> That reframe turns data quality from an infinite cleanliness campaign into a finite design question — where are our detection points, and are they upstream of the ship line? It's also, not coincidentally, exactly what the people consuming your reports actually care about. No executive has ever asked for a data quality score. They ask whether they can put this number in front of the board.</p>

    <h2>The three capabilities that move the discovery point.</h2>
    <span class="h2-sub">Monitoring, response, and an honest ledger</span>

    <p><strong>1. Checks that run before the report ships.</strong> Not a platform — a habit, often a dozen lines of logic. Do the totals reconcile to the source system? Is the row count within a sane range of last period's? Is the data actually fresh, or is yesterday wearing today's date? Did a null-rate or a top-ten list change in a way that no business event explains? Most of the errors that ever reach a boardroom would have tripped one of these four wires. The checks don't need to be sophisticated; they need to exist, and they need to run <em>before</em> distribution, not after the first confused reply-all.</p>

    <p><strong>2. A fast, honest correction process.</strong> Some errors will ship anyway. What happens in the next four hours determines whether the episode costs trust or, strangely, earns it. The pattern that works is boringly consistent: correct the number, notify everyone who received the wrong one — proactively, before they find it themselves — and say plainly what was wrong, why, and what now prevents it. A team that corrects fast and openly is demonstrating exactly the rigor people want to believe in. A team that quietly swaps the number and hopes nobody screenshotted the old one is teaching its audience to keep screenshots.</p>

    <p><strong>3. A known-issues log that's actually visible.</strong> Every environment has known imperfections — the source field that's unreliable before the 5th, the region whose CRM hygiene lags, the metric that's directional rather than exact. Pretending otherwise is how those caveats get rediscovered, publicly, at the worst moment. Writing them down — what's affected, what the workaround is, who's fixing it, by when — does two things at once: it stops known issues from masquerading as fresh errors, and it signals that the team knows its own data cold. Counterintuitively, a visible list of known flaws makes reporting <em>more</em> credible, not less. Confessed imperfection reads as competence; discovered imperfection reads as negligence.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <h3>The pre-flight checks that catch most of it</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Reconciliation:</strong> headline totals match the source system, within a stated tolerance.</li>
        <li><strong>Volume:</strong> row counts are within a sane range of the prior period — big silent jumps and drops get flagged.</li>
        <li><strong>Freshness:</strong> the last successful load is verified, so stale data can't wear today's date.</li>
        <li><strong>Shape:</strong> null rates and the top-ten entities haven't shifted in ways no business event explains.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Quality is a process property, not a data property.</h2>
    <span class="h2-sub">Which is good news</span>

    <p>Notice what all three capabilities have in common: none of them is about making the data better. They're about making the <em>process</em> around the data trustworthy — detection before distribution, candor after it, and a standing record of what's known. That's good news, because process is cheap to change and entirely within the team's control, in a way that upstream data entry and vendor feeds never will be. It also explains a pattern that confuses a lot of leaders: why a modest team with disciplined checks is trusted more than a sophisticated stack without them. The trust was never coming from the technology. It was coming from where the errors got caught.</p>

    <div class="tip">
      <div class="tlabel">Where to start right now</div>
      <p>Take the last error that reached leadership — every organization has one — and run the post-mortem nobody ran at the time: at which of the five discovery points <em>could</em> it have been caught, and what single check would have caught it there? Build that one check this week. Then repeat with the next incident. Three or four iterations of this builds most of a monitoring layer, scoped by real failures instead of speculation. For a broader read on where your environment stands — error handling included — the free <a href="/resources/#checklist">Reporting Trust Health Check</a> scores all ten areas in about three minutes, no email required.</p>
